The '''''Pluton'' class [[minelayer]]s''' were a pair of ships built just before [[World War I]] for the [[French Navy]] as their first purpose-built minelayers. They spent the first few months of the war laying [[minefield]]s off captured [[Belgian]] ports and in the [[English Channel]] in conjunction with British ships. ''Pluton'' remained there for the rest of the war, but ''Cerbère'' was transferred to the eastern [[Mediterranean Sea]] in 1915. The ship laid minefields off the [[Syria]]n coast and the [[Dardanelles]]. Later in the war she laid minefields in the southern [[Adriatic]] as well. Both ships were struck from the Navy List in 1921 and sold for [[ship breaking|scrap]].

==Design and description==
The French Navy noted the effectiveness of [[Naval mine|mines]] during the [[Russo-Japanese War]] of 1904–05 and experimented with them by converting two elderly [[torpedo]]-[[gunboat]]s in 1911–12. They were not very successful and the French concluded that specially designed ships were necessary. Two new minelayers were ordered as part of the 1912 Naval Program, {{ship|French minelayer|Pluton||2}} and {{ship|French minelayer|Cerbère||2}}, the first purpose-built minelayers of the French Navy.<ref name=s8>Simpson, p. 228</ref>

===General description===
The ''Pluton''-class ships had an [[length overall|overall length]] of {{convert|199|ft|5|in|m|1}} and a [[length between perpendiculars]] of {{convert|193|ft|7|in|m|1}}. They had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|27|ft|3|in|m|1}}, and a draft of {{convert|14|ft|2|in|m|1}}. The ships displaced {{convert|565|LT|t}} at normal load and {{convert|594|LT|MT}} at [[deep load]].<ref name=s8/>

''Pluton'' and ''Cerbère'' were given rudders at bow and stern for the precision maneuvering deemed by the navy to be necessary for their mission. Their hulls were subdivided into ten watertight compartments by transverse [[Bulkhead (partition)|bulkhead]]s. They had a crew of three officers and 49 men.<ref name=s1/>

===Propulsion===
They were powered by two [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|vertical triple-expansion steam engines]], each driving a single [[propeller shaft]]. The engines developed a total of {{convert|6000|ihp|lk=in}} from two [[water-tube boiler]]s. On [[sea trial]]s the ships reached a maximum speed of {{convert|21.5|kn|lk=in}}. The ''Pluton''-class ships carried a maximum of {{convert|180|LT|MT}} of coal which gave them a range of {{convert|1900|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|16|kn}}.<ref name=s1>Simpson, pp. 228, 231</ref>

===Armament===
The ''Pluton''-class ships were armed with a single {{convert|75|mm|0|adj=on|sp=us}} gun mounted in front of the [[bridge (nautical)|bridge]]. They carried 140 {{convert|550|kg|adj=on|sp=us|0}} Sauter-Harle mines. The mines were carried on trolleys that ran on four rails on the mine deck that led to two doors in the stern of the ship, from which they were dropped.<ref name=s31>Simpson, p. 231</ref>

==Service==
''Cerbère'' was laid down in August 1911<ref>{{cite book|last=Brassey|first=Thomas|authorlink=Thomas Brassey, 2nd Earl Brassey|title=The Naval Annual 1913|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NQJAAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA36&ots=ajMK9ZyU0m&dq=minelayer%20cerbere&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=1913|publisher=J. Griffin|location=Portsmouth, England|page=36}}</ref> and launched on 13 July 1912 by [[Chantiers Normand]] in [[Le Havre]]''.<ref name=g6/> Pluton'' was launched on 10 March 1913 by [[Ateliers & Chantiers de Bretagne]] in [[Nantes]].<ref name=s8/> Both ships were completed in 1914 and were assigned to the Northern Squadron ({{lang-fr|Escadre du Nord}}) in the English Channel under the command of Admiral Rouyer when World War I began.<ref name=s31/> ''Pluton'' captured the German merchant ship SS ''Porto'' in the Channel on 5 August 1914.<ref name=g6>Gardiner and Grey, p. 216</ref> For the rest of 1914 they laid [[minefield]]s off [[Ostende]], [[Zeebrugge]] and other ports in German-occupied Flanders, often in conjunction with, and at the request of, the [[Royal Navy]].<ref name=s31/>
While ''Pluton'' spend the rest of the war in the Channel, ''Cerbère'' was transferred to the Mediterranean in 1915. She laid minefields mostly off the Syrian coast and the Dardanelles before joining the Anglo-French naval force on 31 May 1916 that pressured the Greek government into acceding to Allied demands for control of Greek communications and transportation infrastructure.<ref>Newbolt, p. 142</ref> The ship spent the rest of the war operating in the southern Adriatic as well as the eastern Mediterranean. Both ships were deemed surplus to requirements after the end of the war and were scrapped in 1921.<ref name=s31/>

